<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    SECURITY FINDING: [M5] Insecure Communication — Cleartext Traffic Allowed

    OWASP Mobile Top 10 2024: M5
    MASVS:  MSTG-NETWORK-2
    CWE:    CWE-319 (Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information)
    Risk:   HIGH

    DESCRIPTION:
    This configuration explicitly allows cleartext (HTTP) traffic to all domains.
    Any data transmitted over HTTP is visible to anyone on the same network segment —
    coffee shop Wi-Fi, corporate proxy, ISP, rogue access point.

    This means:
    - Auth tokens sent in HTTP headers are captured by Wireshark/tcpdump
    - User credentials sent in POST body are readable in plaintext
    - Session cookies are intercepted and replayed for session hijacking
    - API responses containing PII are exposed to passive eavesdroppers

    Combined with the disabled certificate validation in InsecureApiClient.kt,
    this app is trivially attacked with a MITM proxy (Burp Suite, mitmproxy).

    ATTACK STEPS:
    1. Configure Burp Suite proxy on same network as device/emulator
    2. Set emulator proxy to Burp Suite's IP:8080
    3. Install Burp's CA certificate on the emulator
    4. All HTTP traffic is captured in plaintext — auth tokens, passwords, PII

    REMEDIATION:
    - Remove cleartextTrafficPermitted="true" — default is false on API 28+
    - Enforce HTTPS for all endpoints including internal/debug ones
    - Implement certificate pinning for sensitive endpoints (see MASTG guidance)
    - Use network_security_config.xml to pin specific certificates, not to loosen security
-->
<network-security-config>

    <!--
        [M5] VULNERABILITY: Cleartext traffic allowed globally.
        Default on API 28+ is cleartextTrafficPermitted="false" — this overrides it.
        The api_base_url in strings.xml uses HTTP — this config is what makes it work.
    -->
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true">
        <trust-anchors>
            <!-- [M5] VULNERABILITY: Trusting user-installed certificates -->
            <!-- Allows Burp Suite and mitmproxy CA certs to be trusted automatically -->
            <!-- Attackers install their proxy CA to intercept all TLS traffic -->
            <certificates src="system" />
            <certificates src="user"/>   <!-- VULNERABILITY: never trust user certs in prod -->
        </trust-anchors>
    </base-config>

    <!--
        REMEDIATION (commented out — what this SHOULD look like):
    -->
    <!--
